### Permitted Purpose

A Permitted Purpose is any purpose other than a Competing Use.

A **Competing Use** means use of the Software, or any derivative work
of the Software, in a product, service, or offering that competes with
any Softprobe commercial product or service. A product, service, or
offering competes with Softprobe if both of the following are true:

1. It is offered or made available, directly or indirectly, to third
   parties (i.e., parties other than the licensee and its Affiliates);
   **and**

2. It provides substantially the same functionality as a Softprobe
   commercial product or service, including but not limited to:

   (a) HTTP, gRPC, or other RPC traffic capture;
   (b) HTTP, gRPC, or other RPC traffic replay or playback;
   (c) session-based mocking or service virtualization for testing
       purposes;
   (d) record-and-replay regression testing across microservices;
   (e) topology-aware test orchestration driven by captured traffic;
   (f) any hosted, managed, SaaS, on-premises, embedded, bundled,
       white-labeled, or otherwise-distributed form of any of the
       above.

For clarity, Competing Use is **not limited** to hosted or managed
services. Distributing the Software — or a product containing the
Software — to third parties as a packaged on-premises product, an
appliance, a library, a CLI tool, a plugin, a cloud marketplace
listing, or as any component of a larger product, where that product
competes with Softprobe under the criteria above, is also a Competing
Use.

For further clarity, Permitted Purposes explicitly include using the
Software:

1. For your own internal business operations and testing, at any scale,
   including production traffic capture and replay against your own
   workloads;

2. For non-commercial education;

3. For non-commercial research, except for use that results in or
   directly supports any Competing Use;

4. In connection with professional services (e.g., consulting,
   training, implementation, or support services) that you provide to
   a licensee using the Software in accordance with these Terms and
   Conditions — **provided that** those professional services are not
   themselves structured as a Competing Use (for example, a hosted
   "managed testing" service built on top of the Software for third
   parties is a Competing Use even if delivered under a services
   contract);

5. To evaluate the Software for a duration of up to sixty (60) days
   prior to entering into a commercial license with us, including for
   the purpose of benchmarking against Competing Uses you do not then
   deploy.

"Affiliates" of a licensee means any legal entity that controls, is
controlled by, or is under common control with the licensee, where
"control" means direct or indirect ownership of more than fifty
percent (50%) of the voting equity of such entity.

